    questions: [
      { q: 'Tell me about a time you had to troubleshoot a complex system failure under pressure.', type: 'behavioral', tip: 'Use STAR format. Describe your systematic debugging process — what data you collected, how you isolated the root cause, and the quantified outcome. Example structure: "The system was failing X% of the time... I analyzed the data and found... The fix reduced failures to Y%."' },
      { q: 'Describe a project where you had to move fast and ship something imperfect. How did you decide what to cut?', type: 'behavioral', tip: 'Meta values speed over perfection. Show you can prioritize and iterate. Describe: the urgency, what you shipped first (MVP), what you deferred, and how you iterated. Never say "I always deliver perfect work."' },
      { q: 'Walk me through how you would design a test system for a new piece of hardware from scratch.', type: 'technical', tip: 'Walk through the full lifecycle: requirements → test specifications → fixture design → instrumentation selection → data acquisition pipeline → control software → validation → deployment → monitoring. Show you think end-to-end.' },
      { q: 'How do you handle disagreements with engineers who have a different technical approach?', type: 'behavioral', tip: 'Show openness (Meta value "Be Open"). Describe using data to resolve disagreements, not authority or opinion. Best answers include a time you changed YOUR mind based on someone else\'s data.' },
      { q: 'Explain your experience with data acquisition and sensor integration. What sensors have you worked with?', type: 'technical', tip: 'Be specific about sensor types, signal conditioning, sampling rates, data pipelines, and analysis tools. Name the actual parts and protocols (I2C, SPI, UART, etc.). Vague answers like "I worked with sensors" won\'t pass.' },
      { q: 'Tell me about the biggest impact you\'ve had in your current role. How do you measure it?', type: 'behavioral', tip: 'Lead with the number, then explain. Example structure: "I reduced X by Y%, saving Z hours per year. I measure it by..." Concrete metrics are mandatory — estimates are okay if you explain the methodology.' },
      { q: 'How would you approach qualifying a new robotic system for production use?', type: 'technical', tip: 'Cover: requirements definition, risk analysis, test plan (functional/stress/endurance/safety), execution with known-good and known-bad samples, acceptance criteria review, deployment plan, ongoing monitoring.' },
      { q: 'Describe a time you had to learn a new technology quickly to solve a problem.', type: 'situational', tip: 'Show resourcefulness and speed. Structure: "I needed to do X but had never done it. I gave myself Y days. I started with Z tutorials/docs. By end of the week I had a working solution." Emphasize the practical outcome, not the learning journey.' },
      { q: 'How do you prioritize when you have multiple projects competing for your time?', type: 'behavioral', tip: 'Show impact-based prioritization (Meta value: Focus on Impact). Best answer: describe your framework (production impact > time savings > feature requests), give a real example of saying no or deferring something low-impact.' },
      { q: 'Walk me through your experience with failure analysis and root cause investigation.', type: 'technical', tip: 'Use a real example. Show structured methodology: data collection → pattern analysis → hypothesis → testing → root cause → corrective action. Mention specific tools (data visualization, statistical analysis, 5 Whys, fishbone diagram).' },
      { q: 'What\'s the most innovative solution you\'ve built? Why was it innovative?', type: 'behavioral', tip: 'Innovation doesn\'t have to be a new invention. It can be applying an existing approach to a new domain, or building something nobody thought to build. Focus on the insight that made it novel, not just the technology.' },
      { q: 'How do you ensure quality and reliability in systems you deploy?', type: 'technical', tip: 'Cover: test plans, acceptance criteria, monitoring/alerting, documentation, preventive maintenance, and how you track reliability metrics (MTBF, failure rates, yield).' },
      { q: 'Tell me about a time you mentored someone. What was the outcome?', type: 'leadership', tip: 'Focus on HOW you structured their development — not just "I helped them." Describe: scope definition, milestones, feedback cadence, how you matched tasks to their skill level, and the concrete outcome they delivered.' },
      { q: 'Where do you see yourself in 5 years?', type: 'behavioral', tip: 'Show growth ambition aligned with the company\'s trajectory. "Leading a program" is better than "managing people." Connect your 5-year vision to the kind of work this role leads to. Don\'t say "your job."' },
      { q: 'Why Meta? Why this role specifically?', type: 'behavioral', tip: 'Must be specific — generic "great company" is a red flag. Connect YOUR specific experience to THIS specific role. Reference something from the job description. Mention Meta values naturally. If it\'s a Redmond role, mention location if relevant.' },
    ],
    studyGuide: [
      { icon: '1', text: '<strong>STAR Method</strong> — Situation (2 sentences), Task (1 sentence), Action (bulk of answer — what YOU did), Result (quantified). Every behavioral answer needs this structure. Practice 10-12 stories out loud.' },
      { icon: '2', text: '<strong>Meta\'s 5 Values</strong> — Move Fast, Focus on Impact, Be Open, Build Social Value, Live in the Future. Weave these naturally into answers. Don\'t say "I demonstrate Move Fast" — tell a story that shows it.' },
      { icon: '3', text: '<strong>Technical Depth</strong> — Be ready to whiteboard your biggest project\'s architecture: components, data flow, decision rationale. Expect "why did you choose X over Y?" follow-ups on every technical choice.' },
      { icon: '4', text: '<strong>System Design Practice</strong> — Practice designing systems from scratch. Requirements → architecture → components → data pipeline → acceptance criteria. Meta interviews often include design exercises.' },
      { icon: '5', text: '<strong>Metrics — Memorize Cold</strong> — Know your impact numbers instantly: percentages, hours saved, cost reductions, accuracy rates, team sizes, document counts. Hesitating on your own numbers kills credibility.' },
      { icon: '6', text: '<strong>2-3 Minutes Per Answer</strong> — Time yourself. Under 1 min = too shallow. Over 4 min = rambling. Practice hitting the 2-3 minute sweet spot.' },
      { icon: '7', text: '<strong>"Why Meta?" Must Be Specific</strong> — Research the team, the product, the scale. Reference something specific from the job description. Generic answers like "Meta is a great company" are instant red flags.' },
      { icon: '8', text: '<strong>Prepare Questions to Ask</strong> — "What does the first 90 days look like?", "What\'s the biggest technical challenge?", "How does the team measure success?", "What\'s the team culture like day-to-day?" Never say "I don\'t have any questions."' },
      { icon: '9', text: '<strong>Practice Out Loud</strong> — Recording yourself reveals filler words ("um", "like", "so basically"), pacing issues, and unclear structure. Do at least 3 mock interviews before the real one.' },
      { icon: '10', text: '<strong>Failure Stories</strong> — Prepare 2-3 genuine failures with real lessons. Disguised success stories ("my weakness is I work too hard") are transparent and hurt you. Vulnerability + learning = strong answer.' },
    ],
